Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Halve, peel, and finely chop the @red onion{1}. Peel and finely chop the @carrots{6%ounce}. Mince or grate the @garlic{2%cloves}. Remove and discard the ribs and stems from the @kale{4%ounce}, then coarsely chop the leaves. Drain and rinse the @cannellini beans{1%13.4 ounce can}. Remove the @sweet Italian pork sausage{9%ounce} from the casings.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tablespoon} in a large #pot{} over medium-low heat. Add the onion, carrot, garlic, and @chili flakes{1/4%teaspoon}(or less, to taste) to the pot. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, tossing occasionally, for ~{5-6%minutes}, until the veggies have softened. Add the sausage and cook, breaking the meat up into pieces, until browned, for ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add the @diced tomatoes{1%14 ounce can}, cannellini beans, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, and 3 cups water to the pot. Bring to a boil, then reduce to a simmer for ~{10%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

Prepare the Parmesan croutons: halve the @ciabatta bread{1} horizontally. Drizzle each side with olive oil and sprinkle with the @Parmesan cheese{1%ounce}. Place the ciabatta on a #baking sheet{} and transfer to the oven for about ~{5%minutes}, or until bread is toasted and cheese has melted.

Add the kale to the pot and cook, covered, until the kale has wilted, for about ~{3%minutes}. Taste and season with salt and pepper, if necessary.

Cut the Parmesan croutons into cubes. Ladle the ribollita into #bowls{} and top with the croutons so they soak up all the yummy broth! Enjoy!

> Our take on the beloved Ribollita is ideal for this time of year. Sweet Italian sausage adds intense flavor to the dish, but our favorite addition is the cheesy croutons—perfect for soaking up all that yummy broth!